"{\n  \"type\": \"theorem\",\n  \"name\": \"Maximum Distance to Ellipsoid\",\n  \"hypothesis\": [],\n  \"conclusion\": \"The points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0) on the ellipsoid  \\( x^{2}+2 y^{2}+3 z^{2}=1 \\) have the largest distance from the origin.\",\n  \"status\": \"proved\",\n  \"proof\": {\n    \"type\": \"proof\",\n    \"steps\": [\n      {\n        \"type\": \"problem\",\n        \"statement\": \"Find the maximum distance from the origin to the surface defined by the constraint  $x^2 + 2y^2 + 3z^2 = 1$.\",\n        \"solved\": true,\n        \"answer\": \"The maximum distance from the origin to the surface is 1, achieved at the points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0).\",\n        \"proof\": {\n          \"type\": \"proof\",\n          \"steps\": [\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"Instead of maximizing the distance $r$, we can maximize $r^2 = x^2 + y^2 + z^2$, since $r$ is always positive and $r^2$ is maximized whenever $r$ is maximized.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"let\",\n              \"variable\": \"f(x,y,z)\",\n              \"value\": \"$x^2 + y^2 + z^2$\",\n              \"kind\": \"function\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"We want to maximize $f$ subject to the constraint $g(x,y,z) = x^2 + 2y^2 + 3z^2 - 1 = 0$.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"Since both $f$ and $g$ are infinitely differentiable, we can use the method of Lagrange multipliers.  We seek points where the gradients of $f$ and $g$ are parallel:\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"$\\\\nabla f = \\\\lambda \\\\nabla g$, where $\\\\lambda$ is a Lagrange multiplier.\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"$\\\\nabla f = (2x, 2y, 2z)$, $\\\\nabla g = (2x, 4y, 6z)$\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"Therefore, we need to solve the system of equations\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"$2x = 2\\\\lambda x$\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"$2y = 4\\\\lambda y$\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"$2z = 6\\\\lambda z$\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"cases\",\n              \"on\": \"x\",\n              \"split-kind\": \"condition\",\n              \"proof-cases\": [\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"case\",\n                  \"condition\": \"$x \\\\neq 0$\",\n                  \"proof\": {\n                    \"type\": \"proof\",\n                    \"steps\": [\n                      {\n                        \"type\": \"assert\",\n                        \"claim\": \"$\\\\lambda = 1$\",\n                        \"deduced_from\": [\"$2x = 2\\\\lambda x$\"]\n                      },\n                      {\n                        \"type\": \"assert\",\n                        \"claim\": \"$y = 0$\",\n                        \"deduced_from\": [\"$\\\\lambda = 1$\", \"$2y = 4\\\\lambda y$\"]\n                      },\n                      {\n                        \"type\": \"assert\",\n                        \"claim\": \"$z = 0$\",\n                        \"deduced_from\": [\"$\\\\lambda = 1$\", \"$2z = 6\\\\lambda z$\"]\n                      }\n                    ]\n                  }\n                },\n                {\n                  \"type\": \"case\",\n                  \"condition\": \"$x = 0$\",\n                  \"proof\": {\n                    \"type\": \"proof\",\n                    \"steps\": [\n                      {\n                        \"type\": \"cases\",\n                        \"on\": \"y\",\n                        \"split-kind\": \"condition\",\n                        \"proof-cases\": [\n                          {\n                            \"type\": \"case\",\n                            \"condition\": \"$y \\\\neq 0$\",\n                            \"proof\": {\n                              \"type\": \"proof\",\n                              \"steps\": [\n                                {\n                                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                                  \"claim\": \"$\\\\lambda = 1/2$\",\n                                  \"deduced_from\": [\"$2y = 4\\\\lambda y$\"]\n                                },\n                                {\n                                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                                  \"claim\": \"$z=0$\",\n                                  \"deduced_from\": [\"$\\\\lambda = 1/2$\", \"$2z = 6\\\\lambda z$\"]\n                                }\n                              ]\n                            }\n                          },\n                          {\n                            \"type\": \"case\",\n                            \"condition\": \"$y = 0$\",\n                            \"proof\": {\n                              \"type\": \"proof\",\n                              \"steps\": [\n                                {\n                                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                                  \"claim\": \"$z \\\\neq 0$\",\n                                  \"deduced_from\": [\"$x=0$\", \"$y=0$\", \"$g(x,y,z)=0$\"]\n                                },\n                                {\n                                  \"type\": \"assert\",\n                                  \"claim\": \"$\\\\lambda = 1/3$\",\n                                  \"deduced_from\": [\"$2z = 6\\\\lambda z$\"]\n                                }\n                              ]\n                            }\n                          }\n                        ]\n                      }\n                    ]\n                  }\n                }\n              ]\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"Solving for  $x$, $y$, and $z$ in each of these cases and using the constraint equation $g(x,y,z) = 0$, we find the following possible solutions:\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"assert\",\n              \"claim\": \"(1, 0, 0), (-1, 0, 0), (0, 1/sqrt(2), 0), (0, -1/sqrt(2), 0), (0, 0, 1/sqrt(3)), (0, 0, -1/sqrt(3))\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"remark\",\n              \"statement\": \"Evaluating $r^2 = x^2 + y^2 + z^2$ at each of these points, we find that the maximum value of $r^2$ is 1, achieved at the points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0).\"\n            },\n            {\n              \"type\": \"conclude\",\n              \"statement\": \"Therefore, the maximum distance from the origin to the surface is 1, achieved at the points (1, 0, 0) and (-1, 0, 0).\"\n            }\n          ]\n        }\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}"